## Set up Firebase Authentication in Next.js (App Router)

### 1. Install dependencies
```
npm install firebase firebase-admin
```
- `firebase` — client-side SDK (browser)
- `firebase-admin` — server-side SDK (Node.js / Route Handlers)

Do NOT install `@firebase/auth` separately — it is included in `firebase`.

### 2. Create a Firebase project
- Go to https://console.firebase.google.com, create a project.
- In **Project Settings → General**, add a Web App and copy the config.
- In **Authentication → Sign-in method**, enable the providers you want (Google, Email/Password).
- In **Project Settings → Service accounts**, generate a new private key and save the JSON file.

### 3. Environment variables
Add to `.env.local`:
```
# Client (public)
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=AIza...
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-app.firebaseapp.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-app
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-app.appspot.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=123456789
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=1:123456789:web:abc

# Server only (never NEXT_PUBLIC_)
FIREBASE_ADMIN_PROJECT_ID=your-app
FIREBASE_ADMIN_CLIENT_EMAIL=firebase-adminsdk-xxx@your-app.iam.gserviceaccount.com
FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
```
NEVER commit `.env.local`. NEVER prefix server-side Firebase Admin credentials with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`.

### 4. Firebase client SDK (`lib/firebase/client.ts`)
```ts
import { initializeApp, getApps, getApp } from 'firebase/app';
import { getAuth } from 'firebase/auth';

const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY,
  authDomain: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN,
  projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID,
  storageBucket: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET,
  messagingSenderId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID,
  appId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID,
};

// Prevent re-initialization in Next.js hot reload
const app = getApps().length > 0 ? getApp() : initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
export const auth = getAuth(app);
```
Always guard with `getApps().length > 0` to prevent duplicate app initialization during Next.js dev hot-reload.

### 5. Firebase Admin SDK (`lib/firebase/admin.ts`)
```ts
import { initializeApp, getApps, cert, App } from 'firebase-admin/app';
import { getAuth } from 'firebase-admin/auth';

let adminApp: App;

if (!getApps().length) {
  adminApp = initializeApp({
    credential: cert({
      projectId: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_PROJECT_ID,
      clientEmail: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_CLIENT_EMAIL,
      // Replace \\n with actual newlines (env var may encode them)
      privateKey: process.env.FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY?.replace(/\\n/g, '\n'),
    }),
  });
} else {
  adminApp = getApps()[0];
}

export const adminAuth = getAuth(adminApp);
```
This file must ONLY be imported in Server Components, Route Handlers, and middleware — never in client components.

### 6. Auth context (React, Client Components)
Create `components/auth/firebase-auth-provider.tsx`:
```tsx
'use client';
import { createContext, useContext, useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import type { User } from 'firebase/auth';
import { onAuthStateChanged } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

interface AuthContextValue {
  user: User | null;
  loading: boolean;
}

const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue>({ user: null, loading: true });

export function FirebaseAuthProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    const unsubscribe = onAuthStateChanged(auth, async (firebaseUser) => {
      setUser(firebaseUser);
      if (firebaseUser) {
        // Sync session cookie with server
        const idToken = await firebaseUser.getIdToken();
        await fetch('/api/auth/session', {
          method: 'POST',
          headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
          body: JSON.stringify({ idToken }),
        });
      }
      setLoading(false);
    });
    return () => unsubscribe();
  }, []);

  return <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, loading }}>{children}</AuthContext.Provider>;
}

export const useAuth = () => useContext(AuthContext);
```
Wrap your root layout with `<FirebaseAuthProvider>`.

### 7. Session cookie API route (`app/api/auth/session/route.ts`)
This endpoint exchanges a Firebase ID token for a server-side session cookie:
```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import { adminAuth } from '@/lib/firebase/admin';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

const SESSION_DURATION_MS = 60 * 60 * 24 * 5 * 1000; // 5 days

export async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
  try {
    const { idToken } = await req.json() as { idToken: string };
    const sessionCookie = await adminAuth.createSessionCookie(idToken, {
      expiresIn: SESSION_DURATION_MS,
    });
    const cookieStore = await cookies();
    cookieStore.set('__session', sessionCookie, {
      httpOnly: true,
      secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
      sameSite: 'lax',
      maxAge: SESSION_DURATION_MS / 1000,
      path: '/',
    });
    return NextResponse.json({ status: 'ok' });
  } catch {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Invalid token' }, { status: 401 });
  }
}

export async function DELETE() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  cookieStore.delete('__session');
  return NextResponse.json({ status: 'ok' });
}
```

### 8. Server-side session helper (`lib/auth/get-session.ts`)
Read and verify the session cookie in Server Components or middleware:
```ts
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
import { adminAuth } from '@/lib/firebase/admin';

export async function getSession() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const sessionCookie = cookieStore.get('__session')?.value;
  if (!sessionCookie) return null;
  try {
    const decoded = await adminAuth.verifySessionCookie(sessionCookie, true);
    return decoded;
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
}
```
Use in Server Components:
```ts
import { getSession } from '@/lib/auth/get-session';
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const session = await getSession();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  return <div>Welcome {session.email}</div>;
}
```

### 9. Sign in with Google (client)
```tsx
'use client';
import { signInWithPopup, GoogleAuthProvider, signOut } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

const provider = new GoogleAuthProvider();

export function GoogleSignInButton() {
  const signIn = async () => {
    await signInWithPopup(auth, provider);
    // onAuthStateChanged in the provider handles the rest
  };

  const handleSignOut = async () => {
    await signOut(auth);
    await fetch('/api/auth/session', { method: 'DELETE' });
    window.location.href = '/';
  };

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={signIn}>Sign in with Google</button>
      <button onClick={handleSignOut}>Sign out</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

### 10. Sign in with Email/Password
```tsx
import { signInWithEmailAndPassword, createUserWithEmailAndPassword } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

// Sign up
await createUserWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);

// Sign in
await signInWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);
```

### 11. Protect routes with middleware
Create `middleware.ts` at the project root:
```ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

const PROTECTED_PATHS = ['/dashboard', '/settings', '/api/protected'];

export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const session = req.cookies.get('__session')?.value;
  const isProtected = PROTECTED_PATHS.some((p) => req.nextUrl.pathname.startsWith(p));
  if (isProtected && !session) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login', req.url));
  }
  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/:path*', '/settings/:path*', '/api/protected/:path*'],
};
```
Note: Middleware cannot run `firebase-admin` — it runs on the Edge runtime. The full `verifySessionCookie` check belongs in Server Components or Route Handlers.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Firebase: Error (auth/configuration-not-found)`** — `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_*` env vars are missing or not prefixed correctly. Check `.env.local` and restart the dev server.
- **`Error: Firebase app named '[DEFAULT]' already exists`** — You are calling `initializeApp` without the `getApps().length` guard. Use the singleton pattern from steps 4 and 5.
- **`Error: private key is not valid`** — The `FIREBASE_ADMIN_PRIVATE_KEY` newlines are escaped as `\n` in the env file. Add `.replace(/\\n/g, '\n')` as shown in step 5.
- **Session cookie not set / 401 on `/api/auth/session`** — The ID token has expired (they last 1 hour). Call `user.getIdToken(true)` to force a refresh, or let `onAuthStateChanged` handle it automatically.
- **`auth/unauthorized-domain`** — Your app's domain is not in Firebase's **Authentication → Settings → Authorized domains**. Add `localhost` for dev and your production domain.
- **Server Component imports firebase client SDK** — `firebase` client SDK is browser-only. Import `@/lib/firebase/admin` on the server and `@/lib/firebase/client` only in client components or `'use client'` files.
- **User is null after page refresh** — `onAuthStateChanged` re-resolves asynchronously after refresh; show a loading skeleton while `loading === true`.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT prefix server-side Firebase Admin credentials with `NEXT_PUBLIC_` — this exposes your service account to the browser.
- Do NOT import `firebase-admin` in client components or files without `'use client'` — it will fail at build time.
- Do NOT import the Firebase client SDK in Server Components or Route Handlers — it is browser-only code.
- Do NOT call `initializeApp` without checking `getApps().length` first — you will get a 'duplicate app' error on hot reload.
- Do NOT verify the session cookie in Edge middleware — `firebase-admin` requires Node.js. Use a presence check in middleware and full verification in Server Components.
- Do NOT store the Firebase ID token in `localStorage` as your only auth mechanism — ID tokens expire in 1 hour. Use session cookies via the Admin SDK for persistent sessions.
- Do NOT disable the `httpOnly` flag on the session cookie — doing so makes it accessible to JavaScript and vulnerable to XSS.
